# 1️⃣ Retention Policies in Azure Blob Storage

A **Retention Policy** defines **how long data must be kept before it can be deleted or modified**.

It is mainly used for:

* Compliance
* Audit logs
* Financial data
* Security logs

## Types of Retention in Blob Storage

### 1. Soft Delete Retention

Soft delete keeps deleted blobs for a **configured number of days** so they can be recovered.

Example:

```
Retention: 7 days
```

Workflow:

```
Blob Deleted
     ↓
Soft Delete Enabled
     ↓
Stored in recovery state (7 days)
     ↓
Permanent deletion after 7 days
```

Use Case:

* Application accidentally deletes files
* DevOps can restore them quickly.

---

### 2. Immutable Storage (Legal Hold / Time-based retention)

This prevents blobs from being **modified or deleted** until a defined period.

Example:

```
Retention Period = 1 year
```

Common industries:

* Banking
* Healthcare
* Government compliance

Workflow:

```
Upload file
      ↓
Apply retention policy
      ↓
File locked for X days
      ↓
Deletion allowed only after policy expiry
```

---

# 2️⃣ Storage Policies (Lifecycle Management)

A **Lifecycle Management Policy** automatically **moves data between storage tiers** or deletes old data.

This is used to **reduce storage cost automatically**.

Example policy:

```
Hot Tier → Cool Tier after 30 days
Cool Tier → Archive Tier after 90 days
Delete after 365 days
```

Example JSON policy:

```json
{
 "rules": [
  {
   "name": "log-management",
   "enabled": true,
   "type": "Lifecycle",
   "definition": {
    "actions": {
     "baseBlob": {
      "tierToCool": { "daysAfterModificationGreaterThan": 30 },
      "tierToArchive": { "daysAfterModificationGreaterThan": 90 },
      "delete": { "daysAfterModificationGreaterThan": 365 }
     }
    },
    "filters": {
     "blobTypes": ["blockBlob"],
     "prefixMatch": ["logs/"]
    }
   }
  }
 ]
}
```

Example folder structure:

```
storage-account
   ├── logs/
   │     ├── app.log
   │     ├── error.log
```

After 30 days:

```
Hot → Cool
```

After 90 days:

```
Cool → Archive
```

---

# 3️⃣ Storage Tiers in Blob Storage

In **Azure Blob Storage**, data is stored in **3 tiers**.

| Tier    | Usage                          | Cost                 |
| ------- | ------------------------------ | -------------------- |
| Hot     | Frequently accessed data       | Highest storage cost |
| Cool    | Infrequent access              | Medium               |
| Archive | Rare access (long term backup) | Lowest               |

Example:

```
Hot → Active logs
Cool → Monthly reports
Archive → Old backups
```

---

# 4️⃣ How Files Move Between Tiers

Files can move between tiers in **three ways**.

---

## Method 1 — Lifecycle Policy (Automatic)

Azure automatically moves files.

Example:

```
Day 0   → Upload log file
Day 30  → Move to Cool
Day 90  → Move to Archive
Day 365 → Delete
```

This runs **once per day automatically**.

---

## Method 2 — Azure CLI

DevOps engineers can manually move files using CLI.

Example:

Move blob to Cool tier

```
az storage blob set-tier \
--account-name mystorage \
--container-name logs \
--name app.log \
--tier Cool
```

Move blob to Archive tier

```
az storage blob set-tier \
--tier Archive
```

---

## Method 3 — Azure Portal

Steps:

```
Azure Portal
 → Storage Account
 → Containers
 → Select Blob
 → Change Access Tier
```

---

# 5️⃣ Rehydration Process (Archive → Hot)

Archive blobs cannot be read instantly.

They must be **rehydrated first**.

Example workflow:

```
Archive Blob
      ↓
Rehydrate request
      ↓
Move to Hot or Cool
      ↓
Accessible after 12 hours
```

Rehydration types:

| Type          | Time           |
| ------------- | -------------- |
| Standard      | up to 15 hours |
| High priority | 1 hour         |

---

# 6️⃣ Real DevOps Example (Production)

### Scenario

Application logs stored in blob storage.

Daily log size:

```
200 GB/day
```

If logs stay in **Hot tier**, cost becomes very high.

Solution:

Lifecycle policy:

```
logs/

0–30 days  → Hot
30–90 days → Cool
90–365 days → Archive
Delete after 1 year
```

Benefits:

* 70–90% storage cost reduction
* Automated storage management

---

